			<TextBlock Grid.Row="9" Grid.Column="0" Text="SUBJECT:   "/>
			<TextBlock Grid.Row="9" Grid.Column="1" Grid.ColumnSpan="3" Text="US/Soviet Conflict in Maritime Domain"/>
		  </Grid>
		  <TextBlock Grid.Row="2" TextWrapping="Wrap">
1. I attach here a rather stunning array of indicators regarding the recent Soviet aggressive activities in the Norwegian Sea and the Bering Strait. It appears that while the initial conflict was started due to the overreach of an individual SAG commander, Soviet High Command used the opportunity to capitalize upon our surprise.
<LineBreak/>
<LineBreak/>
2. The engagement in the Bering Strait initially bolstered Soviet hopes for a swift gain of key territories, weakening in particular our Early Warning capabilities. We should maintain careful watch on isolated radar stations, particularly in the North Pacific.
<LineBreak/>
<LineBreak/>
3. However, the loss of a Ballistic Missile Submarine as it approached the SOSUS Barrier has caused significant recriminations within the Soviet Strategic Rocket Forces, and Naval Commands. The shock of a significant loss has increased the Soviet's desire to keep conflict isolated, and looks likely to push them towards more realistic negotiations.
<LineBreak/>
<LineBreak/>
